er than i thought it would be, so be mindful about how much time you devote to the process - making a 'project' icon can easily consume half a day and result in nothing usable from a design perspective :).    \r\n\r\nthe default size of the icons included in uikit seems to be 20 x 20.\r\n\r\nan example of their svg code in `uikit/src/images/icons/check.svg` is:\r\n```svg  \r\n<svg width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\r\n    <polyline fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#000\" stroke-width=\"1.1\" points=\"4,10 8,15 17,4\" />\r\n</svg>\r\n```\r\nso my goal was to generate svg code that kind of looked like that.  \r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 01:**  \r\n\r\ncreate an illustrator file with some background screenies of your interface, a yellow colored 20 x 20pt 'icon container' layer, and your icon objects.  \r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_01](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392036-e98b2a00-9b3e-11e9-9571-5852ba08e28f.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 02:**\r\n\r\nselect the yellow 'icon container' layer, hide all layers except it and your icon objects, and go to:\r\n\r\n`Object` > `Artboards` > `Fit to Selected Art`\r\n\r\nthis will shrink your artboard to the size of your 'icon container' layer.\r\n\r\n***important:  make sure you \"undo\" this step after you have exported your svg file so that you retain your original artboard dimensions - the \"undo\" history is not limitless in illustrator, so if you make lots of changes after shrinking your artboard, you might not be able to \"undo\" back to the point in time when your artboard was larger***\r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_02](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392085-b1381b80-9b3f-11e9-8cc3-824b2056a3b2.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 03:**\r\n\r\nhide the yellow 'icon container' layer so you still have a 20 x 20 artboard and go to:\r\n\r\n`File` > `Export` > `Export for Screens`\r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_03](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392124-6ec30e80-9b40-11e9-8a95-52c6225221ae.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 04:**\r\n\r\nmake sure `Artboards` is selected so you export the full 20 x 20 area.  \r\n\r\nselect `svg` as the format, and then click the settings icon.  \r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_04](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392153-d2e5d280-9b40-11e9-9c27-61dfa33e0a96.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 05:**\r\n\r\nthese settings seemed to produce the code that most closely resembled the default uikit icon's code.  \r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_05](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392162-f741af00-9b40-11e9-8fe2-d320e4c668a6.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 06:**\r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_06](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392173-10e2f680-9b41-11e9-8db4-a47092350b94.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 07:**\r\n\r\nan svg file will be generated in the folder you chose in the previous step.  \r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_07](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392183-2e17c500-9b41-11e9-87b0-629a40b14ed6.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 08:**\r\n\r\nopen the svg file in your editor and it should look pretty much like the default uikit icon code, the only extra bit being a `<title>` tag, which can be removed.  \r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_08](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392204-6b7c5280-9b41-11e9-8e92-e43bd9537afd.png)\r\n\r\n---   \r\n\r\n**step 09:**\r\n\r\nto preserve any colors in your icon, you might need to add the `uk-preserve` class to the icon span.  \r\n\r\n![making_a_svg_step_09](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5090307/60392209-9070c580-9b41-11e9-9808-c5b9ab86e929.png)\r\n\r\n"},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/uikit/uikit/issues/3901","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/uikit/uikit","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/uikit/uikit/issues/3901/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/uikit/uikit/issues/3901/comments","events_url":"https://a